                            <body>
                                <p> HONG KONG, Sept 23 (Reuters) - The trial of three activists  for organising an unauthorised rally began in a Hong Kong court  on Monday, the first prosecution under a tough public order law  which was enacted when the city returned to China.</p>
                                <p> Rights activists and commentators say the trial shows Hong  Kong's Beijing-backed administration is getting bolder in  curbing dissenting voices, five years into Chinese rule.</p>
                                <p> The trio -- well-known activist Leung Kwok-hung and student  leaders Fung Ka-keung and Lo Wai-ming -- have been charged for  violating the Public Order Ordinance, which requires protesters  to seek prior police approval at least seven days in advance.</p>
                                <p> All pleaded not guilty. It was not immediately clear what  penalties they could face if convicted.</p>
                                <p> They say they did not try to obtain a police permit before  staging a protest on February 10 against a five-month jail  sentence slapped on a social worker for obstructing police and  assaulting a policeman in a demonstration last August.</p>
                                <p> The trial is expected to last five days.</p>
                                <p> Pro-democracy groups are alarmed by the trial and some 200  people took to the streets on Sunday in a show of support for  the three men. They say the charges violate Hong Kong's  constitution, which guarantees the right to peaceful assembly,  procession and demonstration in the territory.</p>
                                <p> "More and more people are afraid of expressing their hopes  and their longing for freedom and justice. It's important that  no law should curb the freedom of expression," Catholic priest  Franco Mella said on Sunday during the march.</p>
                                <p> Legal experts say the charges could trigger a new legal  battle over whether the ordinance is constitutional.</p>
                                <p> The charges are the first ever brought under the ordinance  despite dozens of protests for which police received no prior  notice, according to legal observers.</p>
                                <p> The trial also comes as the Hong Kong government is  expected to enact a new law to ban all acts of subversion,  treason, sedition and secession against the mainland  government.</p>
                                <p> Rights circles fear this anti-subversion law, which Hong  Kong is required to introduce under its constitution, will  further curb civil rights and freedoms.    </p>
